1
00:00:30,296 --> 00:00:31,831
- I like to be center stage

2
00:00:33,299 --> 00:00:34,667
taking the big parts.

3
00:00:34,701 --> 00:00:38,505
I'm not interested
in being worthy,

4
00:00:38,538 --> 00:00:40,774
I'm not interested
in being virtuous

5
00:00:40,807 --> 00:00:43,610
and standing there for
the good of the company.

6
00:00:43,643 --> 00:00:45,545
I'm simply not
interested in that.

7
00:00:45,578 --> 00:00:47,147
It's the way I'm constructed.

8
00:00:47,180 --> 00:00:50,283
It's my own megalomaniacal
selfishness, I suppose.

9
00:00:50,316 --> 00:00:52,452
I'm not interested in
all that experimentation,

10
00:00:52,485 --> 00:00:56,322
and we've all got a knuckle
under and obey the director.

11
00:00:56,356 --> 00:00:57,457
I say, bollocks.

12
00:00:58,858 --> 00:01:01,461
- In 1991, in
The Silence of the Lambs

13
00:01:01,494 --> 00:01:02,662
by Jonathan Demme,

14
00:01:02,695 --> 00:01:05,732
Anthony Hopkins achieves
worldwide success,

15
00:01:05,765 --> 00:01:09,803
playing a cannibalistic
psychopath imprisoned in a cage.

16
00:01:09,836 --> 00:01:14,574
The most famous serial killer
of all time, Hannibal Lecter.

17
00:01:14,607 --> 00:01:15,842
Even though he was on screen

18
00:01:15,875 --> 00:01:17,911
for only 20 minutes
throughout the movie,

19
00:01:17,944 --> 00:01:20,613
it's enough to propel him
to the top of Hollywood

20
00:01:20,647 --> 00:01:22,449
at almost 60 years old,

21
00:01:22,482 --> 00:01:24,617
and after more than
30 years of acting.

22
00:01:25,752 --> 00:01:27,587
The biggest directors
fight over him,

23
00:01:27,620 --> 00:01:31,191
like Francis Ford Coppola
who casts him in Dracula.

24
00:01:31,224 --> 00:01:32,425
- Action!

25
00:01:34,561 --> 00:01:36,162
- Mina!

26
00:01:37,464 --> 00:01:39,265
- The thing is going
to happen pretty fast.

27
00:01:39,299 --> 00:01:40,500
- Yes.
- You confront them,

28
00:01:40,533 --> 00:01:41,801
they attack you,

29
00:01:41,835 --> 00:01:43,336
Van Helsing challenges you,

30
00:01:43,369 --> 00:01:46,239
you make your lay statement
and then you leave.

31
00:01:46,272 --> 00:01:47,841
- Even Steven
Spielberg wants him

32
00:01:47,874 --> 00:01:51,177
to play the president of the
United States in Amistad.

33
00:01:51,211 --> 00:01:52,445
- Yeah.

34
00:01:52,479 --> 00:01:53,613
- And you're coming down
with your secretary.

35
00:01:53,646 --> 00:01:54,881
This was something,
you can trial this.

36
00:01:54,914 --> 00:01:56,549
But this is a better location.

37
00:01:56,583 --> 00:01:57,851
- Good.
- So we'll do that first.

38
00:01:57,884 --> 00:01:58,518
- And have you seen the
house of the General?

39
00:01:58,551 --> 00:01:59,853
- No.

40
00:01:59,886 --> 00:02:01,387
- Come here, because
you're going to love this.

41
00:02:01,421 --> 00:02:03,923
- 1992 is a
turning point for him.

42
00:02:03,957 --> 00:02:07,360
In addition to becoming the
favorite actor of James Ivory,

43
00:02:07,393 --> 00:02:09,429
it's also the year
that he is cemented

44
00:02:09,462 --> 00:02:11,464
among the greatest
actors of all time

45
00:02:11,498 --> 00:02:14,601
for his iconic role in
The Silence of the Lambs.

46
00:02:15,702 --> 00:02:18,671
- And the Oscar goes
to Anthony Hopkins

47
00:02:18,705 --> 00:02:20,540
in The Silence of The Lambs.

48
00:02:21,808 --> 00:02:23,576
- I sat there that
evening in the Oscars

49
00:02:23,610 --> 00:02:27,947
and Ted Tally picked up
the best screenplay writer.

50
00:02:27,981 --> 00:02:31,584
And at that moment I thought,
"I think I've got the Oscar,"

51
00:02:31,618 --> 00:02:35,421
and Kathy Bates came
on stage to present it

52
00:02:35,455 --> 00:02:37,657
and I knew she was
going to call my name.

53
00:02:40,627 --> 00:02:41,961
First of all, before I say on,

54
00:02:41,995 --> 00:02:44,664
I want to say
hello to my mother.

55
00:02:44,697 --> 00:02:46,866
She's in Wales watching
this on television

56
00:02:47,934 --> 00:02:50,770
with Eve and Jean
and Jill and Tony.

57
00:02:50,803 --> 00:02:52,906
My father died 11
years ago tonight,

58
00:02:52,939 --> 00:02:55,775
so maybe he had something to
do with this as well.

59
00:02:55,808 --> 00:02:58,244
And then I thought when I got
up there to take the Oscar,

60
00:02:58,278 --> 00:03:00,313
I thought, "Well now I
can do some bad films,"

61
00:03:00,346 --> 00:03:01,781
which I proceeded to do.

62
00:03:01,814 --> 00:03:02,916
Doesn't matter really.

63
00:03:04,384 --> 00:03:06,953
I touched the ceiling
of my life, I suppose.

64
00:03:07,987 --> 00:03:10,823
I love the coldness of life.

65
00:03:10,857 --> 00:03:13,993
I love the
inevitability of it all.

66
00:03:19,666 --> 00:03:24,671
I had no friends, because I
rejected friends, I suppose.

67
00:03:24,704 --> 00:03:26,005
So I was lonely.

68
00:03:26,039 --> 00:03:27,707
I was a non-starter.

69
00:03:28,641 --> 00:03:30,276
Very poor student.

70
00:03:31,844 --> 00:03:33,513
I was convinced I was
on the wrong planet.

71
00:03:36,950 --> 00:03:39,452
I think that those years
were quite formative for me.

72
00:03:39,485 --> 00:03:41,788
I was escaping, I
think, from my sense

73
00:03:41,821 --> 00:03:43,856
of being a kind of clodhopper.

74
00:03:48,361 --> 00:03:49,696
Well, I was the source of worry.

75
00:03:49,729 --> 00:03:50,997
I was the only child and
I was the source of worry

76
00:03:51,030 --> 00:03:52,599
of both my parents
when I was a kid,

77
00:03:52,632 --> 00:03:54,701
because I was so
stupid at school.

78
00:03:54,734 --> 00:03:56,669
I mean, I haven't got
fashionable high flowing words

79
00:03:56,703 --> 00:03:57,637
like, I was dyslexic,

80
00:03:57,670 --> 00:03:58,838
I think I was just stupid.

81
00:03:58,871 --> 00:04:01,774
And I couldn't figure out
what anyone was talking about.

82
00:04:01,808 --> 00:04:04,410
And I was the lonely kid
at the top of the streets

83
00:04:04,444 --> 00:04:05,712
staring at my thumbnail,

84
00:04:05,745 --> 00:04:07,380
and all the other kids were down

85
00:04:07,413 --> 00:04:08,548
the other end of the street.

86
00:04:08,581 --> 00:04:09,816
My father used to
say to my mother,

87
00:04:09,849 --> 00:04:11,551
"There's something very
wrong with this boy."

88
00:04:11,584 --> 00:04:15,021
Which is not the way to
give one self-confidence,

89
00:04:15,054 --> 00:04:17,357
but they were worried about me.

90
00:04:17,390 --> 00:04:19,859
But in a strange way, I
had an idyllic childhood.

91
00:04:19,892 --> 00:04:21,828
I remember the first
four years very clearly.

92
00:04:21,861 --> 00:04:23,963
I've got one of those,
cursed and blessed

93
00:04:23,997 --> 00:04:29,369
with images and a
very long memory.

94
00:04:30,436 --> 00:04:32,438
I can remember back
to very early times,

95
00:04:32,472 --> 00:04:35,475
probably about the age of
two, something like that.

96
00:04:35,508 --> 00:04:38,978
And I remember South Wales.

97
00:04:39,012 --> 00:04:40,880
I was born in the rural
part of Port Talbot,

98
00:04:40,913 --> 00:04:42,749
a place called Margam.

99
00:04:42,782 --> 00:04:45,818
And it really was like
the Garden of Eden.

100
00:04:45,852 --> 00:04:47,553
I remember our
little front garden,

101
00:04:47,587 --> 00:04:48,521
and it was really...

102
00:04:48,554 --> 00:04:50,356
a couple of small trees there,

103
00:04:50,390 --> 00:04:53,126
and it really was
like a mini paradise.

104
00:04:53,159 --> 00:04:56,029
And I can recall,
when I close my eyes,

105
00:04:56,062 --> 00:04:59,432
I can go back there and it's
all changed now, of course,

106
00:04:59,465 --> 00:05:04,637
but I can, the smells
and the colors.

107
00:05:05,538 --> 00:05:06,906
But when I went to school,

108
00:05:06,939 --> 00:05:08,875
that was the beginning of
the turning point for me.

109
00:05:08,908 --> 00:05:10,576
When I realized I was different,

110
00:05:11,778 --> 00:05:14,047
backward, more slow.

111
00:05:14,080 --> 00:05:15,615
And I have no regret at all,

112
00:05:15,648 --> 00:05:17,550
because that was the
fire in the belly

113
00:05:17,583 --> 00:05:20,053
that gave me enough
anger and rage.

114
00:05:23,990 --> 00:05:29,362
My father was a pretty
boisterous, tough
old sort, really.

115
00:05:30,129 --> 00:05:31,164
He was a remarkable man.

116
00:05:31,197 --> 00:05:32,532
I loved him very much.

117
00:05:34,033 --> 00:05:35,601
He was a baker by profession.

118
00:05:35,635 --> 00:05:36,903
That's what he started.

119
00:05:36,936 --> 00:05:40,073
And he took over, he was
a baker with his father.

120
00:05:40,106 --> 00:05:41,140
Good God.

121
00:05:42,675 --> 00:05:44,444
Believe it or not
I lived in here.

122
00:05:46,179 --> 00:05:48,414
It's just like in my dreams.

123
00:05:48,448 --> 00:05:49,782
Ruins.

124
00:05:49,816 --> 00:05:52,752
Maybe it's a symbol
of my own ruined life.

125
00:05:52,785 --> 00:05:53,820
I don't know.

126
00:05:54,821 --> 00:05:57,156
And I remember that sometimes,

127
00:05:57,190 --> 00:05:59,125
the yellow look in his
face around the gills,

128
00:05:59,158 --> 00:06:00,693
and the sweat.

129
00:06:01,627 --> 00:06:04,063
And he'd say, "Oh God."

130
00:06:04,097 --> 00:06:06,999
And he'd do that, and I remember
that God, he's worked hard.

131
00:06:09,168 --> 00:06:13,005
Yeah, I think that's why
I get angry sometimes.

132
00:06:14,707 --> 00:06:15,975
- Do you think of
your father often now?

133
00:06:16,008 --> 00:06:16,943
- All the time.

134
00:06:16,976 --> 00:06:18,177
- Yes.

135
00:06:18,211 --> 00:06:18,745
- And as I get older,
he's becoming me.

136
00:06:18,778 --> 00:06:19,879
I'm him.

137
00:06:21,180 --> 00:06:22,515
I remember I used to
play the piano a lot.

138
00:06:22,548 --> 00:06:23,750
I was a little
artist, you could say.

139
00:06:23,783 --> 00:06:24,951
I used to play Beethoven
and all that stuff,

140
00:06:24,984 --> 00:06:26,152
and Chopin, and all that.

141
00:06:26,185 --> 00:06:27,854
And he was a baker,

142
00:06:27,887 --> 00:06:30,189
and he used to ask me to come
and help him in the shop.

143
00:06:30,223 --> 00:06:32,892
Carry the cakes into the
shop during school holidays.

144
00:06:32,925 --> 00:06:35,528
Well I'd sort of get distracted.

145
00:06:35,561 --> 00:06:37,063
And I remember sitting
at the top of the house

146
00:06:37,096 --> 00:06:38,030
where this piano was,

147
00:06:38,064 --> 00:06:39,031
and I remember him coming out,

148
00:06:39,065 --> 00:06:40,733
and "For God sakes," he'd say,

149
00:06:40,767 --> 00:06:42,535
"I asked you to take those
donuts into the shop."

150
00:06:42,568 --> 00:06:43,803
"What the hell are
you doing up here?"

151
00:06:43,836 --> 00:06:45,004
I was playing the piano.

152
00:06:45,037 --> 00:06:46,139
"So what's that you're playing?"

153
00:06:46,172 --> 00:06:47,607
I remember him
standing in the doorway

154
00:06:47,640 --> 00:06:49,509
and he had flour dust
in the hair on his arms.

155
00:06:49,542 --> 00:06:50,777
Really hard worker.

156
00:06:50,810 --> 00:06:51,644
He said, "What are you playing?"

157
00:06:51,677 --> 00:06:52,979
I said, "Beethoven."

158
00:06:53,012 --> 00:06:55,014
He said, "No wonder you
went deaf."

159
00:06:58,518 --> 00:07:00,686
I don't know what my
role in the world is.

160
00:07:01,788 --> 00:07:03,022
I came out here many years ago

161
00:07:03,055 --> 00:07:05,925
because I wanted to be
in movies, be an actor.

162
00:07:05,958 --> 00:07:07,894
I was a bad boy.

163
00:07:09,729 --> 00:07:11,564
I couldn't stand
the British theater.

164
00:07:11,597 --> 00:07:12,799
I couldn't stand any of it,

165
00:07:12,832 --> 00:07:15,067
because I didn't feel
I belonged there.

166
00:07:15,101 --> 00:07:16,769
Nobody's fault.

167
00:07:16,803 --> 00:07:20,807
I just didn't have it in my
nature to be part of that group.

168
00:07:20,840 --> 00:07:22,642
So I reinvented my life,

169
00:07:22,675 --> 00:07:24,210
and I came out here
some years ago,

170
00:07:24,243 --> 00:07:25,545
and you see the result of it.

171
00:07:25,578 --> 00:07:28,147
I'm pretty feisty.

172
00:07:28,181 --> 00:07:30,082
I am rebellious and happy.

173
00:07:32,985 --> 00:07:35,521
And so I want to
give back to people.

174
00:07:35,555 --> 00:07:37,557
Not because I'm on a
crusade, far from it.

175
00:07:37,590 --> 00:07:39,692
I just do this because I've
got nothing better to do.

176
00:07:39,725 --> 00:07:41,627
They give me a cup of coffee
and some fruit in the morning.

177
00:07:41,661 --> 00:07:42,995
So it keeps me off the streets,

178
00:07:43,029 --> 00:07:44,130
keeps me out of trouble,

179
00:07:44,163 --> 00:07:45,264
and I get some fun doing it.

180
00:07:45,298 --> 00:07:46,933
These pretty
beautiful girls here.

181
00:07:46,966 --> 00:07:48,134
Women, women.

182
00:07:49,235 --> 00:07:50,169
- They're beautiful.

183
00:07:50,203 --> 00:07:51,170
I get hugs from them all.

184
00:07:51,204 --> 00:07:52,638
It's very nice.

185
00:07:52,672 --> 00:07:54,841
- Some of the men
hug me as well.

186
00:07:54,874 --> 00:07:56,676
But it's lovely to
see them opening up,

187
00:07:56,709 --> 00:07:59,078
and if that's their response,
then that makes me happy.

188
00:08:02,215 --> 00:08:05,551
- In 1965,
after five years on stage

189
00:08:05,585 --> 00:08:07,220
in Cardiff and then in London,

190
00:08:07,253 --> 00:08:10,056
he is noticed by the legendary
playwright and actor,

191
00:08:10,089 --> 00:08:11,290
Sir Laurence Olivier,

192
00:08:11,324 --> 00:08:14,894
who invites him to join him
in the Royal National Theatre.

193
00:08:16,362 --> 00:08:20,333
Hopkins becomes his understudy
and eventually replaces him.

194
00:08:20,366 --> 00:08:23,002
In his memoir, Laurence
Olivier writes,

195
00:08:23,035 --> 00:08:26,339
"An exceptionally promising
young actor from the company,

196
00:08:26,372 --> 00:08:30,276
named Anthony Hopkins,
replaced me and played my role

197
00:08:30,309 --> 00:08:33,579
as a cat with a mouse
between its teeth."

198
00:08:35,748 --> 00:08:38,317
- Yeah, when I started out
I just wanted to be famous.

199
00:08:38,351 --> 00:08:39,919
I didn't want to
become a great actor.

200
00:08:39,952 --> 00:08:41,721
I didn't want to become a
great Shakespearean actor.

201
00:08:41,754 --> 00:08:43,055
I had no idea.

202
00:08:43,089 --> 00:08:44,290
When people would say,
"You're the next Olivier."

203
00:08:44,323 --> 00:08:45,725
I didn't want to become
the next Olivier.

204
00:08:45,758 --> 00:08:47,093
I didn't want to stand
in wrinkled tights

205
00:08:47,126 --> 00:08:49,028
on The Old Vic stage
for the rest of my life.

206
00:08:49,061 --> 00:08:51,764
I had ideas beyond that.

207
00:08:58,638 --> 00:09:02,008
I was discontent, I
was angry and fed up.

208
00:09:02,041 --> 00:09:05,878
And I hated being part
of an establishment

209
00:09:05,912 --> 00:09:08,180
and hated doing Shakespeare.

210
00:09:08,214 --> 00:09:09,882
It was all my own making.

211
00:09:09,916 --> 00:09:11,017
I was the enemy
within, you know?

212
00:09:11,050 --> 00:09:12,018
It was all my own making.

213
00:09:12,051 --> 00:09:13,286
It was nobody else's fault.

214
00:09:13,319 --> 00:09:17,924
Everyone did their best
to cater to my needs.

215
00:09:19,392 --> 00:09:21,327
- Were you
drinking at that time?

216
00:09:21,360 --> 00:09:24,897
- Oh yes, but all actors drink.

217
00:09:24,931 --> 00:09:26,732
That was just an
episode in my life,

218
00:09:26,766 --> 00:09:27,867
that's over and done with now.

219
00:09:27,900 --> 00:09:29,869
That's a boring episode of life.

220
00:09:29,902 --> 00:09:31,704
But I don't think it helped,

221
00:09:31,737 --> 00:09:32,972
but I was restless.

222
00:09:33,005 --> 00:09:34,840
I wanted to get out,
and I was frightened.

223
00:09:34,874 --> 00:09:38,177
I was afraid I was taking
on this monumental part,

224
00:09:38,210 --> 00:09:40,146
and I never pretended
that I had the courage

225
00:09:40,179 --> 00:09:42,281
to do these great parts
like Macbeth and King Lear.

226
00:09:42,315 --> 00:09:44,817
I never said I could do them.

227
00:09:44,850 --> 00:09:47,253
I never thought I had
the courage to do them.

228
00:09:53,826 --> 00:09:54,760
I wanted it all.

229
00:09:54,794 --> 00:09:55,895
I wanted to be successful,

230
00:09:55,928 --> 00:09:56,862
and I wanted to be famous,

231
00:09:56,896 --> 00:09:58,364
and I wanted to be in movies.

232
00:09:58,397 --> 00:10:01,167
And I wanted to meet people
like Katharine Hepburn,

233
00:10:01,200 --> 00:10:02,735
and I want to meet
Peter O'Toole,

234
00:10:02,768 --> 00:10:03,836
and I met Peter O'Toole,

235
00:10:03,869 --> 00:10:05,404
and I've met some great people,

236
00:10:05,438 --> 00:10:08,007
some wonderful directors,
some wonderful actors.

237
00:10:08,040 --> 00:10:10,810
Would you say, Father, that
I have the makings of a king?

238
00:10:10,843 --> 00:10:12,712
- Splendid king.

239
00:10:12,745 --> 00:10:15,247
- Would you expect me, Father,
to give up without a fight?

240
00:10:15,281 --> 00:10:16,349
- Of course you'll fight.

241
00:10:16,382 --> 00:10:18,184
I raised you to.

242
00:10:18,217 --> 00:10:19,452
- I don't care what
you offer Phillip,

243
00:10:19,485 --> 00:10:20,987
I don't care what
plans you make,

244
00:10:21,020 --> 00:10:23,856
I'll have the Aquitaine
and Alais and the crown,

245
00:10:23,889 --> 00:10:26,125
I'll not give up one
to get the other.

246
00:10:26,158 --> 00:10:27,860
I won't trade off
Alais or Aquitaine

247
00:10:27,893 --> 00:10:29,261
to that walking pustule!

248
00:10:31,764 --> 00:10:33,265
No, your loving son will not.

249
00:10:34,800 --> 00:10:39,705
I remember the first few days
on the set of Lion in Winter,

250
00:10:40,873 --> 00:10:43,275
and I'd done a movie
test with Peter O'Toole

251
00:10:43,309 --> 00:10:44,944
a few weeks before.

252
00:10:45,878 --> 00:10:48,047
And he was on the test with me

